		<li class="comment byuser comment-author-jik bypostauthor even depth-6" id="comment-195147">
				<div id="div-comment-195147" class="comment-body">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
			<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/02ee400c45c070d8044f80af6838729f?s=32&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D32&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-32 photo' height='32' width='32' />			<cite class="fn"><a href='http://stuff.mit.edu/~jik/' rel='external' class='url'>jik</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		</div>
		
		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://blog.kamens.us/send-later/comment-page-2/#comment-195147">
			October 31, 2012 at 4:00 pm</a>		</div>

		<blockquote><p>Local folders makes sense; I suppose the downside is that when you’re online, they’ll still be saved in local folders and therefore won’t be available if I switch back to gmail in a browser, is that right?</p></blockquote>
<p>Correct.</p>
<blockquote><p>Now should I set send_while_offline preference back to ‘true’? I don’t have a good sense of what it does.</p></blockquote>
<p>If the scheduled send time of a message arrived when you&#8217;re in offline mode, and send_while_offline is true, it&#8217;ll be copied into your Outbox and date-stamped at that time, though it won&#8217;t actually be sent, obviously, until you go back on-line.</p>
<p>If, on the other hand, send_while_offline is false, it won&#8217;t be copied into the Outbox and date-stamped until you go back on-line, so the Date header in the message will reflect when you went back on-line (or shortly after).</p>

		<div class="reply">
					</div>
				</div>
